<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA49">
<l>makiḻala koṉṟēpōṉ māṟumpal yākkai</l>
<l>nekiḻa muyalkiṟpārk kallāṉ – mukiḻvirinta</l>
<l>cōtipōṟ ṟōṉṟuñ cuṭarpoṉ ṉeṭumuṭiyem</l>
<l>mātikāṇ pārkku maritu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Except for those who exert themselves<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here muyalkiṟpārkku, dat. of a participial noun honoric plural to muyal-tal, “to make an effort”, still looks like a form from the old auxiliary construction with kil-tal, “to be able to”, but that does not seem to make sense anymore, and it is more likely that we have to read it an intermediate stage in the formation of the “modern” present tense.</note> so that [their] bodies are so</l>
<l>emaciated that [they] alter to the likeness of a single makiḻ-seed,<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">This stanza appears to advocate a sort of harsh penance for the devotees that is not normally seen as a part of bhakti religiosity and does not have parallels in the Antāti-s.</note></l>
<l>it is difficult for those who [want to] see<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here the customary syntactic pattern of aru with a verbal noun justifies a doubt as to whether to emend the slightly awkward kāṇpārkku to kāṇṭaṟku (difficult “to see”). However, a direct parallel is found in the contemporary Śaivite Antāti of Kāraikkālammaiyar, where verse 45, talking of lord Śiva, ends with kāṇpārkku eḷitu, “he is easy to see”.</note> our First cause with the high</l> 
<l>crown of glowing gold<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Or: “the high crown of glowing gold is difficult [to see] even for those who see our first cause”, i.e. even they can see only part of him.</note> that appears like a blooming radiance.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
